wiktionary.Scrapper_Wiktionary.scrap(lang: str = 'en', workers: int = 1)[source]¶

The main function in Scrapper. Here run multiprocessing, create .bz2 reader, read dump, read pages.

Parameters

  • lang – str The language code. One of: ‘en’, ‘it’, ‘fr’, ‘de’, ‘pt’, ‘ru’, ‘es’. See also: Wiktionary languages.

  • workers – int Number of workers in multiprocessing. If workers=1, then run in single process. Recommendation: workers = 10 (for parallel network requests)

wiktionary.Scrapper_Wiktionary.scrap_one(lang, page)[source]¶

Scrap one page.

It load language module and scrap data from page. Then save to DB.

Parameters

  • lang (str) – Language. Example: ‘en’

  • page (Page) – Page instance.

Returns

class wiktionary.Scrapper_Wiktionary_WikitextParser.Link[source]¶

Bases: wiktionary.Scrapper_Wiktionary_WikitextParser.Container

get_text()[source]¶

[[abc]] gives ‘abc’ [[a|b]] is labelled “b” on this page but links to page “a”. Example: b. [[a]]b gives ab. So does [[a|ab]]: ab. The code [[a|b]]c gives bc, just as [[a|bc]] does. However, all four of these examples will link to page “a”. a[[b]] gives ab. [[a]]:b gives a:b since the colon is outside the end brackets. The same goes for [[Washington]]’s or e-[[mail]]. [[a]]’’b’’ gives ab. (Double apostrophes turn on and off italics.) ‘’[[a]]’’b gives ab. [[a|b]]cd gives bcd, and shows an example of link trailing. [[a]]<nowiki />b gives ab. (The nowiki tag is needed to turn off the so-called “linktrail rules”.) [[a|b]]<nowiki />c gives bc.

ref: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Link
